[src:fullscreen-api/exitfullscreen] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:fullscreen-api/exitfullscreen] The `Document` method **`exitFullscreen()`** requests that the element on this document which is currently being presented in fullscreen mode be taken out of fullscreen mode, restoring the previous state of the screen.
[src:fullscreen-api/exitfullscreen] This usually reverses the effects of a previous call to `Element.requestFullscreen()`.
[src:fullscreen-api/exitfullscreen] A `Promise` which is resolved once the user agent has finished exiting fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/exitfullscreen] If an error occurs while attempting to exit fullscreen mode, the `catch()` handler for the promise is called.
[src:fullscreen-api/exitfullscreen] This example causes the current document to toggle in and out of a fullscreen presentation whenever the mouse button is clicked within it.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] In computing, a **full-screen writing program** or **distraction-free editor** is a text editor that occupies the full display with the purpose of isolating the writer from the operating system (OS) and other applications.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] In this way, one should be able to focus on the writing alone, with no distractions from the OS and a cluttered interface.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Often, distraction-free editors feature a dark background and a text field, with lighter colored text.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] However, most distraction-free editors include customisable user interfaces.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] of programs; extensible & scriptable via any language.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Supports syntax highlighting, programmable, several distraction-free packages available.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Some distraction-free editors support rich text editing.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] These include CreaWriter, TextRoom, and WriteRoom.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] In some cases, this feature turned off per default and must be set by a user.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Currently, only a few distraction-free editors support syntax highlighting.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] CodeRoom is an open source project with the purpose of creating a distraction-free code editor with customisable highlighting schemes.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] The latest version of Marave supports syntax highlighting.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Sublime Text supports a distraction-free full-screen view.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Packages exist for GNU Emacs that turn off various features and reformat the display to a distraction-free layout while retaining syntax highlighting and other features familiar to Emacs users.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Word count is a common feature in these editors.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Other aids can include spell checkers, auto-corrections and quick text templates.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] Many of the programs include timers to pace writing.
[src:fullscreen-api/full-screen-writing-program] FocusWriter and WriteMonkey, among others, include typewriter sound effects.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] The **Fullscreen API** adds methods to present a specific `Element` (and its descendants) in fullscreen mode, and to exit fullscreen mode once it is no longer needed.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] This makes it possible to present desired content—such as an online game—using the user's entire screen, removing all browser user interface elements and other applications from the screen until fullscreen mode is shut off.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] See the article Guide to the Fullscreen API for details on how to use the API.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] The Fullscreen API adds methods to the `Document` and `Element` interfaces to allow turning off and on fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Requests that the user agent switch from fullscreen mode back to windowed mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Returns a `Promise` which is resolved once fullscreen mode has been completely shut off.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Asks the user agent to place the specified element (and, by extension, its descendants) into fullscreen mode, removing all of the browser's UI elements as well as all other applications from the screen.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Returns a `Promise` which is resolved once fullscreen mode has been activated.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] The `fullscreenElement` property tells you the `Element` that's currently being displayed in fullscreen mode on the DOM (or shadow DOM).
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] If this is `null`, the document (or shadow DOM) is not in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] The `fullscreenEnabled` property tells you whether or not it is possible to engage fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] This is `false` if fullscreen mode is not available for any reason (such as the `"fullscreen"` feature not being allowed, or fullscreen mode not being supported).
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] A Boolean value which is `true` if the document has an element currently being displayed in fullscreen mode; otherwise, this returns `false`.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Sent to an `Element` when it transitions into or out of fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Sent to an `Element` if an error occurs while attempting to switch it into or out of fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] The availability of fullscreen mode can be controlled using a Permissions Policy.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] The fullscreen mode feature is identified by the string `"fullscreen"`, with a default allowlist value of `"self"`, meaning that fullscreen mode is permitted in top-level document contexts, as well as to nested browsing contexts loaded from the same origin as the top-most document.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Users can choose to exit fullscreen mode by pressing the ESC (or F11) key, rather than waiting for the site or app to programmatically do so.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Make sure you provide, somewhere in your user interface, appropriate user interface elements that inform the user that this option is available to them.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] In this example, a video is presented in a web page.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Pressing the Enter key lets the user toggle between windowed and fullscreen presentation of the video.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] When the page is loaded, this code is run to set up an event listener to watch for the Enter key.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] This code is called by the event handler above when the user hits the Enter key.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] This starts by looking at the value of the `document`'s `fullscreenElement` attribute.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] If the value is `null`, the document is currently in windowed mode, so we need to switch to fullscreen mode; otherwise, it's the element that's currently in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] Switching to fullscreen mode is done by calling `Element.requestFullscreen()` on the `<video>` element.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreen-api] If fullscreen mode is already active (`fullscreenElement` is not `null`), we call `exitFullscreen()` on the `document` to shut off fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] The **`fullscreenchange`** event is fired immediately after an `Element` switches into or out of fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] This event is sent to the `Element` which is transitioning into or out of fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] To find out whether the `Element` is entering or exiting fullscreen mode, check the value of `Document.fullscreenElement`: if this value is `null` then the element is exiting fullscreen mode, otherwise it is entering fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] In this example, a handler for the `fullscreenchange` event is added to the element whose ID is `fullscreen-div`.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] If the user clicks on the "Toggle Fullscreen Mode" button, the `click` handler will toggle fullscreen mode for the `div`.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] If `document.fullscreenElement` has a value it will exit fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] If not, the div will be placed into fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] Remember that by the time the `fullscreenchange` event is handled, the status of the element has already changed.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] So if the change is to fullscreen mode, `document.fullscreenElement` will point to the element that is now in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] On the other hand, if `document.fullscreenElement` is `null`, fullscreen mode has been canceled.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] What that means to the example code is that, if an element is currently in fullscreen mode, the `fullscreenchange` handler logs the `id` of the fullscreen element to the console.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenchange-event] If `document.fullscreenElement` is `null`, the code logs a message that the change is to leave fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenelement] The **`Document.fullscreenElement`** read-only property returns the `Element` that is currently being presented in fullscreen mode in this document, or `null` if fullscreen mode is not currently in use.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenelement] Although this property is read-only, it will not throw if it is modified (even in strict mode); the setter is a no-operation and it will be ignored.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenelement] The `Element` object that's currently in fullscreen mode; if fullscreen mode isn't currently in use by the `document`, the returned value is `null`.
[src:fullscreen-api/fullscreenelement] If there are multiple elements in fullscreen mode, the topmost (most recently requested) element is returned.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software may offer remote monitoring to manage multiple kiosks from another location.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] An e-mail or text alert may be automatically sent from the kiosk for daily activity reports, or generated in response to problems detected by the software.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Other features allow for remote updates of the kiosk's content and the ability to upload data such as kiosk usage statistics via built-in telemetry tools.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software is used to manage a touchscreen, allowing users to touch the monitor screen to make selections.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] A virtual keyboard eliminates the need for a computer keyboard, thus reducing the surface areas vulnerable to vandalism.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software enables digital signage devices to operate in a dedicated mode, ensuring that the devices run for a specified purpose, thereby providing additional security compared to normal mode use.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk system software addresses security by deterring users from maliciously attacking or hacking into the kiosk.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software must be able to prevent misuse of the provided features.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Of equal importance is the ability of the software to limit non malicious users to specific, predetermined activities so the device can be used for a specific task, communication, action or function.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software is a critical component to protecting public facing devices from hackers, inadvertent misuse, and unauthorized access.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software has the facility for an administrator to configure the software to suit the users and limit user behavior.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Administrators can enable or disable parts of the kiosk software via secure log in.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] It is critical that the kiosk software prevent the user from ever reaching the desktop or file system.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] This type of security can be difficult because standard print dialog allows the content to be printed to a file and enable the user access to the file system.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] The same is true for many email links that load the default email tool and allows the email to be saved to a file.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software is available for most all operating systems: Android, iOS, ChromeOS, Linux, Windows, etc.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] It also can be found to support various browsers, most commonly Internet Explorer, Safari, Firefox and Google Chrome.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk software is also an option for projects that may not even be using kiosk hardware.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Windows PCs and Chrome devices can be configured to run in “kiosk mode” which prevents users from accessing certain system functions.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] For Windows, this may not be appropriate for all uses, since running in kiosk mode may not give deployers the amount of control they need for their final end product configuration.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] Kiosk system software can be used to secure the kiosk or PC instead.
[src:fullscreen-api/kiosk-software] For those running a Windows OS, an alternative to kiosk software is Group Policy, which serves to restrict user access to certain areas of the operating system, though not without its own drawbacks and security issues.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The **`requestFullscreen()`** method of the `Element` interface issues an asynchronous request to display the element in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] An object that controls the behavior of the transition to fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Controls the selected keyboard lock mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] In this mode, the browser forwards keyboard events to the application that would normally be handled by browser or system code.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Applications should intercept events for the keys and key combinations they want to use, and call `preventDefault()` to cancel any default actions.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Note that some browsers may disable the default action for some keys, such as the key that is normally used to exit fullscreen mode; this is not guaranteed, so you should always call `preventDefault()`.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Browsers are also encouraged to provide a mechanism to exit fullscreen mode with keyboard lock.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] For more information see the Keyboard locking section below.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Controls whether or not to show navigation UI while the element is in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The default value is `"auto"`, which indicates that the browser should decide what to do.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The browser's navigation interface will be hidden and the entire dimensions of the screen will be allocated to the display of the element.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The browser will present page navigation controls and possibly other user interface; the dimensions of the element (and the perceived size of the screen) will be clamped to leave room for this user interface.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The browser will choose which of the above settings to apply.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Specifies on which screen you want to put the element in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] This takes a `ScreenDetailed` object as a value, representing the chosen screen.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] A `Promise` which is resolved with a value of `undefined` when the transition to full screen is complete, or rejects with an exception.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The passed `options.keyboardLock` parameter is not supported by the browser.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The **`requestFullscreen()`** method issues an asynchronous request to display the element in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] If the element has been detached from the original document, then the document receives these events instead.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Additionally, any set `Permissions-Policy` must allow the use of the `fullscreen` feature.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] You can determine whether or not your attempt to switch to fullscreen mode is successful by using the `Promise` returned by `requestFullscreen()`, as seen in the examples below.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] To learn when other code has toggled fullscreen mode on and off, you should establish listeners for the `fullscreenchange` event on the `Document`.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] It's also important to listen for `fullscreenchange` to be aware when, for example, the user manually toggles fullscreen mode, or when the user switches applications, causing your application to temporarily exit fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Keyboard locking allows a fullscreen application to intercept and handle some keys and key combinations that would otherwise be exclusively handled by the browser or the underlying OS.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] This can improve the user experience for games, for example, by allowing the Esc key to be used as a menu key instead of exiting fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] It can also be useful for applications such as remote desktop control, where you want almost all key events to be forwarded to the remote computer.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The keyboard lock is activated by passing a keyboard lock mode value of `"browser"` to the `options.keyboardLock` parameter when activating fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] When keyboard lock is active in fullscreen mode the browser will redirect "many more" keyboard events to the application — the precise set of keys is browser dependent.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The web application should handle the event by first calling `preventDefault()` to cancel its default action.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Some key combinations are used for system control or have privacy risks, and hence cannot be intercepted and disabled using this mechanism (for example, Ctrl+Alt+Delete on Windows).
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Note that some browsers always disable the default action for the Esc key when in keyboard lock, so that pressing it doesn't automatically exit fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] However, as this is not guaranteed, you will still need to call `preventDefault()` to stop Esc key presses from exiting fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] More generally, you can't assume that the default action for any keyboard event is disabled by default.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Browsers are expected to provide an alternative mechanism for exiting fullscreen mode when keyboard lock is enabled.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Most browsers use the Esc key to exit normal fullscreen mode, and a long-press Esc key to exit keyboard lock.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The keyboard lock is disabled when the browser exits fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The user has to interact with the page or a UI element in order for this feature to work.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Fullscreen mode is controlled by the Permissions-Policy directive `fullscreen`.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The default allowlist for `screen-wake-lock` is `self`.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] This allows fullscreen usage in same-origin nested frames but prevents them in third-party content.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] Third party usage can be enabled by the server first setting the `Permissions-Policy` header to grant permission a particular third party origin.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The Permissions API `fullscreen` permission can be used to test whether access to use the mode is `granted`, `denied` or `prompt` (requires user acknowledgement of a prompt).
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] This example toggles the `<video>` element in and out of fullscreen mode when the Enter or Shift + F keys are pressed.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The script checks whether the document is currently in fullscreen using `document.fullscreenElement`.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] If the document is in fullscreen, it calls `document.exitFullscreen()` to exit.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] This example is almost the same as the previous example, except that we request that fullscreen is opened with keyboard lock.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The modified key event listener code is shown below.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The first difference is that we handle the event for the Esc key in fullscreen mode, calling `event.preventDefault()` to disable the default action (which would be to exit fullscreen mode).
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] As before we call `requestFullscreen()` if Enter or Shift+F are pressed when not in fullscreen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] However in this case we pass the `keyboardLock` option with the value `"browser"`.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] When the page displays full frame, note the temporary notification at the top of the page that explains how to exit full screen mode.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] In this example, the entire document is placed into fullscreen mode by calling `requestFullscreen()` on the document's `Document.documentElement`, which is the document's root `<html>` element.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The promise's resolve handler does nothing, but if the promise is rejected, an error message is displayed by calling `alert()`.
[src:fullscreen-api/requestfullscreen] The `Window.getScreenDetails()` method is used to retrieve the `ScreenDetails` object for the current device, which contains `ScreenDetailed` objects representing the different available screens.
